A nice patch of poppies growing my the side of the road in the foothills. An observation for the bee is here - https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/43849497.
Varied Carpet Beetles on a California Poppy in my garden.  The beetles are covered with pollen!
Next to a trail in the foothills above Claremont. Vegetation consisted of sage scrub transitioning to chaparral mixed with non-native grasses and thistles.
Visiting Johnston's Honeysuckle growing beside a dirt fire road in the foothills above Claremont.
Growing beside a dirt fire road in the foothills above Claremont.
Black-tailed Bumble Bee on Red Buckwheat (Eriogonum grande var. rubescens) in my garden.
Narrowleaf Milkweed growing by the side of Johnson's Pasture Road in the Claremont Hills Wilderness Park.

Thisbe's Tarantula Hawk on Narrowleaf Milkweed by the side of Johnson's Pasture Road in the Claremont Hills Wilderness Park.\n\nThe dark subterminal band on the wings with the distal hyaline area shows this to be P. thisbe. The straight antennae indicate that it's a male.
doesn't look like a typical honey bee, help please
California Buckwheat has gone to seed and turned dark red in most spots, but here and there are still a few flowering plants that attract numerous pollinators.
this is for the plant, the butterfly is here: https://inaturalist.ca/observations/6166211
this Sara orange tip was one of four I observed in the area during the walk
With an aggressive Western Honey Bee who tried to push the Metalmark off the Brittlebush flower.
Feeding on Common Fiddleneck (Amsinckia menziesii). Very fast moving, and audible. Possibly Dimorphic?

Ovipositing and feeding on Miner's Lettuce.
Looking through California iNat observations of the species, I saw quite a few with the same host plant, https://www.inaturalist.org/observations?locale=en-US&place_id=14&preferred_place_id=1&taxon_id=346196.
Last year, I found a larva on Miner's Lettuce, https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/42572245.

http://mothphotographersgroup.msstate.edu/species.php?hodges=9868
Also visited lupine and corn poppies but stayed longest on the gilia flowers.
Feeding on a flowering Sugar Bush.
On a Sugar Bush.\nOf all the possibilities, I think it could be E. nadia.\nhttp://mothphotographersgroup.msstate.edu/species.php?hodges=974&state=CA
There are three honey bees and one other (leafcutter?).
Feeding on Black Sage, and resting.
Feeding on Cleveland Sage, a second, hairier individual showing up at the same time as https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/79283768.
Three, feeding side by side on Narrowleaf Milkweed.\nPer https://bugguide.net/node/view/70052:\n"Note the dark submarginal band basal to the hyaline edge of the wing."
much smaller than most of our common skippers
large numbers of the pygmy blue observed this day and this location
several pairs mating on the lupine flowers
Two, on Purple Owl's-Clover. Plant and moth: double love!
This observation relates to the plant; a separate observation has been posted for the white-lined sphinx.
